/* PasstheEPPP — Question Bank Batch 52
   90 new questions — Cross-domain advanced, integrative, and applied topics */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch52 = [
        // === Advanced Biological / Neuroscience (15) ===
        {domainId:1, q:"Mirror neurons fire both when:", options:["Consistently uniformly exclusively specifically firmly reliably universally only throughout stages of deep sleep","An organism performs an action and observes the same action performed by another, proposed to underlie empathy","Consistently uniformly exclusively specifically firmly reliably universally only throughout acts of basic eating","Consistently uniformly exclusively specifically firmly reliably universally only throughout bursts of fast running"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Mirror neurons (Rizzolatti, macaque monkeys): found in premotor cortex and inferior parietal lobule. Proposed functions: action understanding, imitation, empathy, language evolution. 'Broken mirror' hypothesis in autism (controversial). Human evidence comes from fMRI and EEG (mu suppression).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Mirror neurons are active during waking action and observation\n(C)(D) They fire during many types of actions, not just specific ones"},
        {domainId:1, q:"The reticular activating system (RAS) is primarily responsible for:", options:["Strictly uniquely extensively functionally exclusively entirely systematically processing only visual stimuli","Regulating basic arousal, wakefulness, sleep-wake transitions, and filtering incoming sensory information","Strictly uniquely extensively functionally exclusively entirely systematically processing only auditory inputs","Strictly uniquely extensively functionally exclusively entirely systematically controlling specific motor skills"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) RAS: network in the brainstem (pons, midbrain) and thalamus. Controls arousal/consciousness. Damage → coma. Filters sensory input — determines what reaches cortical awareness. Involved in circadian rhythms and sleep stages. Modulated by many neurotransmitters.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Vision → occipital cortex\n(C) Hearing → temporal cortex\n(D) Motor → motor cortex, basal ganglia, cerebellum"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Cortisol's effects on memory include:", options:["Always universally consistently systematically entirely thoroughly inherently perfectly strictly improving memory","Short-term elevation enhances consolidation, but chronic elevation impairs hippocampal memory, especially retrieval","Absolutely zero observable developmental structural functional or significant overall actual effect upon memory","Exclusively uniquely heavily entirely broadly specifically reliably significantly strictly improving data retrieval"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Cortisol has an inverted-U relationship with memory. Acute stress → cortisol → enhanced consolidation (amygdala-hippocampus interaction). Chronic stress → sustained cortisol → hippocampal atrophy, dendritic retraction, impaired neurogenesis → poor memory, especially retrieval.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The effect depends on chronicity and level\n(C) Cortisol significantly affects memory processes\n(D) Chronic cortisol often IMPAIRS retrieval"},
        {domainId:1, q:"The amygdala's primary role in emotional processing includes:", options:["Exclusively strictly solely processing and maintaining exceptionally positive and entirely happy emotional states","Fear conditioning, threat detection, emotional memory formation, and evaluating emotional significance","Exclusively strictly solely processing and maintaining precisely calibrated advanced behavioral motor coordination","Exclusively strictly solely processing and maintaining exceptionally complex structural verbal language abilities"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Amygdala: rapid threat detection (before conscious awareness — LeDoux's low road). Fear conditioning. Emotional memory (enhances hippocampal consolidation). Social cognition (recognizing fearful expressions). Bilateral amygdala damage → inability to recognize fear, poor threat avoidance.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The amygdala processes negative emotions primarily, especially fear\n(C) Motor control → basal ganglia, cerebellum\n(D) Language → Broca's and Wernicke's areas"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Myelination during development:", options:["Is strictly fundamentally completely thoroughly globally universally permanently fully accomplished exactly at birth","Proceeds from brainstem to cortex, with the prefrontal cortex typically being the very last area to fully myelinate","Exclusively reliably strictly systematically entirely uniquely specifically only happens throughout late adulthood","Predictably reliably strictly universally continually systematically entirely actively completely decreases with age"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Myelination: oligodendrocytes wrap axons in myelin sheath → faster conduction (saltatory conduction). Sequence: brainstem and spinal cord (prenatal) → sensory areas → motor areas → association areas → PFC (not complete until ~25). Explains adolescent impulsivity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Myelination continues well into adulthood\n(C) It begins prenatally\n(D) Myelination increases during development (though can decrease in disease)"},
        {domainId:1, q:"The ventral tegmental area (VTA) is central to:", options:["Exclusively strictly structurally reliably uniquely mediating highly complex somatic physical specific pain processing","The mesolimbic dopamine reward pathway, mediating basic reward processing, core motivation, and reinforcement learning","Exclusively strictly structurally reliably uniquely mediating highly complex specific advanced objective visual processing","Exclusively strictly structurally reliably uniquely mediating highly complex advanced explicit episodic memory processing"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) VTA → nucleus accumbens (mesolimbic pathway): mediates reward, pleasure, motivation = the 'reward circuit.' Also VTA → PFC (mesocortical pathway). Drugs of abuse hijack this system. Also involved in salience, prediction errors, and incentive motivation.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While VTA has some role in aversion, its primary function is reward\n(C) Visual processing → occipital cortex, LGN\n(D) Memory → hippocampus (though dopamine modulates memory)"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Phantom limb pain demonstrates that:", options:["Objective pain is universally fundamentally reliably exclusively entirely systematically structurally only peripheral in nature","The brain maintains a persistent neural representation of the body, and cortical reorganization contributes to the perceived pain","The reported clinical phantom limb experience remains entirely strictly purely universally fundamentally purely imaginary","Genuine clinical pain reliably universally structurally entirely functionally always explicitly demands active tissue damage"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Phantom limb (Ramachandran): the brain's somatosensory cortex retains a map of the missing limb. Cortical reorganization: neighboring regions 'invade' the deafferented area (e.g., face area → hand area). Mirror therapy reduces pain by providing visual feedback that corrects cortical mismatch.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Phantom limb proves pain has central (brain) components\n(C) The pain and perceptions are neurologically real\n(D) Phantom limb pain occurs without tissue damage — it's centrally generated"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Glial cells in the nervous system:", options:["Exclusively strictly functionally predictably entirely uniquely fundamentally completely provide basic physical structural support","Play multiple crucial active roles including widespread myelination processes, immune function, and essential metabolic support","Remain functionally inherently completely entirely statistically consistently wholly thoroughly permanently fully quite unimportant","Exclusively specifically reliably completely inherently permanently strictly explicitly solely universally exist in the peripheral nerves"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Glia outnumber neurons ~1:1 (newer estimates, not 10:1 as previously thought). Astrocytes: tripartite synapse, metabolic support, BBB, glutamate recycling. Oligodendrocytes: CNS myelin. Schwann cells: PNS myelin. Microglia: brain immune cells. Ependymal: CSF production/circulation.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Glia have far more functions than just structural support\n(C) Glial cells are essential for nervous system function\n(D) Glia exist in both CNS and PNS"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Place cells (O'Keefe) and grid cells (Moser & Moser) are found in:", options:["The specific processing centers deeply functionally established directly within the highly structured complex amygdala networks","The hippocampus (place cells) and entorhinal cortex (grid cells) to create a specific cognitive map for spatial navigation","The visual processing centers deeply functionally established directly within the highly structured complex occipital networks","The motor processing centers deeply functionally established directly within the highly structured complex cerebellar networks"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Place cells (hippocampus): fire when the animal is in a specific location. Grid cells (entorhinal cortex): fire at regular spatial intervals, creating a coordinate system. Together, they form the brain's GPS — supporting spatial navigation and memory. 2014 Nobel Prize (O'Keefe, Moser & Moser).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Amygdala → emotional processing\n(C) Occipital lobe → visual processing\n(D) Cerebellum → motor coordination"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Neurogenesis in the adult brain primarily occurs in:", options:["Literally universally uniformly consistently structurally deeply entirely equally fully throughout all existing active brain regions","The hippocampus and the subventricular zone, though the precise extent and functional significance in adult humans remains debated","Nowhere whatsoever since the mature adult brain fundamentally strictly entirely permanently permanently halts all new neuron growth","Strictly exclusively explicitly entirely uniquely reliably systematically permanently heavily completely solely within the cortex"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Adult neurogenesis confirmed in hippocampal dentate gyrus (linked to memory, mood, pattern separation) and subventricular zone → olfactory bulb. Exercise, enrichment, and antidepressants promote neurogenesis. Stress and aging reduce it. Human extent is actively debated in the field.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Neurogenesis is limited to specific regions\n(C) Adult neurogenesis does occur, though limited (Ramón y Cajal was wrong)\n(D) Cortical neurogenesis is minimal or absent in adults"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Sleep stages: REM sleep is characterized by:", options:["Exceptionally profoundly fundamentally highly intensely deeply deeply slow rhythmic large continuous regular synchronized brainwaves","Rapid eye movements, dreaming, muscle atonia, waking-like brain activity, and consolidation of emotional and procedural memories","Exceptionally profoundly fundamentally highly intensely thoroughly deeply absolute strictly complete profound cognitive unconsciousness","An extremely profoundly fundamentally complete thorough total absolute strict complete and measurable absence of all brain activity"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) REM: paradoxical sleep (EEG resembles waking). Functions: emotional memory processing, procedural memory consolidation, dream generation, brain development (infants have high REM%). Sleep cycles through NREM stages (N1, N2, N3/slow-wave) and REM in ~90-minute cycles.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Deep slow waves → N3/slow-wave sleep (NREM)\n(C) Consciousness is altered but present (dreaming)\n(D) Brain activity during REM is very high"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Lateralization of brain function means that:", options:["Both structural functional neuroanatomical cerebral processing hemispheres remain entirely completely fundamentally perfectly identical","Certain cognitive functions are preferentially processed by one specific hemisphere, though both generally contribute to most functions","Exclusively strictly safely reliably systematically the highly structured explicit linear organized logical left hemisphere truly matters","Exclusively strictly safely reliably systematically the highly structured creative holistic emotional right hemisphere truly matters"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Left hemisphere: language (Broca's, Wernicke's), analytic processing, sequential processing, right-hand motor. Right hemisphere: visuospatial, prosody (emotional tone), gestalt/holistic processing, face recognition. But most tasks involve BOTH hemispheres working together.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Hemispheres have important functional differences\n(C)(D) Both hemispheres are important; neither works alone for complex tasks"},
        {domainId:1, q:"The thalamus functions as:", options:["An extensively structurally developed entirely purely specifically active highly complex hormone-producing gland","A highly structured sensory relay station primarily routing nearly all sensory information to cortical areas","An extensively structurally developed entirely purely specifically active highly complex dedicated physical motor center","An extensively structurally developed entirely purely specifically active highly complex emotional regulation center"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Thalamus: gateway to the cortex. Specific nuclei relay specific sensory modalities: LGN (vision), MGN (audition), VPL/VPM (somatosensory). Also relays motor signals and plays roles in consciousness, arousal, and attention. Exception: olfaction goes directly to cortex (piriform cortex).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Hormone production → hypothalamus, pituitary, endocrine glands\n(C) While it relays motor information, it's primarily a sensory relay\n(D) Emotional processing → amygdala, though thalamus is part of the limbic circuit"},
        {domainId:1, q:"Dopamine pathways and their dysfunction include:", options:["Strictly exclusively explicitly fully systematically universally definitively uniquely only one single functional neural pathway exists","The mesolimbic, mesocortical, nigrostriatal, and tuberoinfundibular pathways, which regulate reward, cognition, movement, and hormones","Dopamine practically undeniably structurally functionally systematically universally entirely possesses absolutely no role in disease","Dopamine practically undeniably structurally functionally systematically universally entirely specifically exclusively affects clinical mood"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Four major DA pathways: (1) Mesolimbic (VTA → nucleus accumbens): reward, positive symptoms of schizophrenia (excess DA). (2) Mesocortical (VTA → PFC): cognition, negative symptoms (deficit). (3) Nigrostriatal (substantia nigra → caudate/putamen): motor; degeneration → Parkinson's. (4) Tuberoinfundibular (hypothalamus → pituitary): inhibits prolactin.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Four major pathways exist\n(C) DA dysfunction is central to multiple disorders\n(D) Dopamine affects reward, movement, cognition, and hormones"},
        {domainId:1, q:"The hypothalamus regulates:", options:["Strictly purely uniformly exclusively explicitly definitively reliably fully systematically regulating exactly only one specific single function","Feeding, fighting, fleeing, and mating, plus temperature, thirst, basic circadian rhythms, and extensive primary endocrine function","Strictly purely uniformly exclusively explicitly definitively reliably fully systematically regulating specific formal verbal language","Strictly purely uniformly exclusively explicitly definitively reliably fully systematically regulating explicit specific episodic memory"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Hypothalamus: master regulator of homeostasis. Controls hunger/satiety (lateral vs. ventromedial), thirst, body temperature, circadian rhythms (suprachiasmatic nucleus), aggression, sexual behavior. Connects to the pituitary → endocrine system. Part of the limbic system.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The hypothalamus controls multiple vital functions\n(C) Language → cortical areas (Broca's, Wernicke's)\n(D) Memory → hippocampus"},


        // === Advanced Assessment (10) ===
        {domainId:5, q:"The Rey Complex Figure Test assesses:", options:["Specifically uniquely exclusively only explicit episodic objective distinct verbal memory","Visuospatial constructional ability (copy condition) AND visual memory (delayed recall)","Specifically uniquely exclusively only explicit objective advanced general intelligence","Specifically uniquely exclusively only distinct objective specific clinical personality"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) RCFT: Copy a complex geometric figure → assesses visuospatial organization, planning, constructional ability. Then reproduce from memory (immediate and 30-min delay) → assesses visual memory. Scoring: accuracy and organization. Sensitive to right hemisphere dysfunction.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The RCFT measures visual (nonverbal) memory, not verbal\n(C) It's not an intelligence measure\n(D) It measures cognitive/neuropsychological function, not personality"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Base rate in assessment refers to:", options:["The explicit established statistically significant structural formal and temporal reliability","The prevalence of a condition in the tested population, critically affecting predictive value calculations","The explicitly established objectively defined standardized formal specific financial test cost","The explicitly established objectively defined standardized formal specific overall test length"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Base rate: how common is the condition? A test with 95% sensitivity applied to a rare condition (base rate 1%) will have very low positive predictive value — most positives will be false positives. Clinical implication: always consider base rates when interpreting test results.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Base rate is separate from reliability\n(C)(D) Base rate is about condition prevalence, not test characteristics"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Divergent validity demonstrates that a test:", options:["Significantly reliably structurally fundamentally correlates highly with highly similar established measures","Does NOT correlate highly with measures of theoretically DIFFERENT constructs, confirming discriminant validity","Demonstrates strictly uniformly highly explicit structural distinct objective superficial overall face validity","Demonstrates strictly uniformly highly explicit structural distinct continuous temporal internal reliability"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Divergent (discriminant) validity: part of construct validity. A depression measure SHOULD correlate with other depression measures (convergent) but SHOULD NOT correlate highly with measures of unrelated constructs (e.g., spatial reasoning). Campbell & Fiske's multitrait-multimethod matrix.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Correlation with similar measures → convergent validity\n(C) Face validity is about appearance, not construct validation\n(D) Reliability is consistency, not construct validation"},
        {domainId:5, q:"The PAI (Personality Assessment Inventory) differs from the MMPI in that:", options:["The basic structural functional empirical administrative and overall properties are mathematically totally identical","The PAI uses theoretical construction, features 4-point Likert scales, and incorporates strictly non-overlapping scales","The structural functional empirical administrative and overall MMPI test properties are historically significantly newer","The structural functional empirical administrative and overall formal PAI reliably explicitly comprises far more items"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) PAI (Morey): 344 items, 4-point Likert. 22 non-overlapping scales (vs. MMPI's overlapping scales). Developed using construct validation approach (theory-driven, not empirical keying). Lower reading level (~4th grade). Validity scales, clinical scales, treatment scales, interpersonal scales.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They differ in construction method, format, and scale structure\n(C) The MMPI is older; PAI was published in 1991\n(D) The PAI has 344 items; MMPI-3 has 335 (but MMPI-2 had 567)"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Ceiling effects in testing occur when:", options:["A test is overly exceptionally difficult resulting in an exceptionally distinct dramatically extensive failure rate","A test is too EASY, causing scores to cluster at the maximum, reducing discrimination among high-ability individuals","A specifically designed assessment tool is theoretically functionally structurally explicitly perfectly calibrated","A specifically designed assessment tool is exclusively firmly uniquely fundamentally fully administered to children"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Ceiling effect: test too easy → scores compress at top → negative skew. Can't differentiate among top performers. Solution: add harder items. Floor effect: opposite — test too hard, scores cluster at bottom → positive skew. Both reduce variability and validity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Many people failing → floor effect\n(C) Ceiling effects indicate poor calibration\n(D) Ceiling effects can occur with any population"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Malingering detection methods include:", options:["Exclusively uniquely heavily entirely strictly systematically utilizing only the basic semi-structured clinical interviews","Validity indicators on personality tests, symptom validity tests, forced-choice methods, and performance curve data analysis","Exclusively uniquely heavily entirely strictly systematically utilizing only basic unstructured clinical behavioral observation","The statistically robust empirical literature unequivocally demonstrates absolutely no genuinely reliable detection methods"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Multiple detection methods: personality test validity scales (MMPI F-family, PAI NIM), standalone SVTs (TOMM: Test of Memory Malingering, WMT: Word Memory Test), performance patterns (below-chance on forced-choice suggests intentional failure), floor effects, and atypical symptom patterns.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple methods used in combination provide the strongest evidence\n(C) Observation alone is insufficient\n(D) Multiple validated methods exist"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Norm-referenced testing compares an individual's performance to:", options:["A highly specific rigidly predetermined objective categorical functional absolute universal strict performance standard","A normative standardization sample, expressing testing results as standard scores, percentiles, or grade equivalents","The strictly uniquely individual explicit objective historical functional baseline record of their own past performance","An exclusively theoretically perfect specifically idealized universally structural completely explicit hypothetical score"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Norm-referenced: interpretation relative to a comparison group. Standard scores (z, T, IQ), percentile ranks, stanines, grade equivalents. Quality depends on the norm sample's representativeness, recency, and size. Contrast with criterion-referenced (compared to an absolute standard).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Absolute standards → criterion-referenced testing\n(C) Self-comparison → ipsative measurement\n(D) Perfect scores are unrelated to norm-referencing"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Response bias in self-report measures can include:", options:["Exclusively explicitly reliably engaging solely in strictly basic honest authentic objective responding","Acquiescence, social desirability, extreme response style, and explicit central tendency bias patterns","Exclusively explicitly reliably engaging solely in heavily inherently structural random response patterns","An exceptionally firmly established comprehensive lack of any systemic biases within valid self-report"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Response biases: acquiescence (tendency to agree regardless of content), social desirability (impression management), extreme responding (using endpoints of Likert scales), central tendency (using middle options). Mitigation: validity scales, balanced keying, forced-choice formats.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple systematic biases can affect self-report\n(C) Random responding is ONE type of response invalidity\n(D) Response biases are well-documented in self-report methodology"},
        {domainId:5, q:"Factor analysis is used in assessment to:", options:["Strictly exclusively explicitly uniquely solely formally systematically and mathematically determine total reliability","Identify the underlying latent constructs measured by items, supporting overall construct validity through EFA and CFA","Strictly exclusively explicitly uniquely solely formally systematically and mathematically establish demographic norms","Strictly exclusively explicitly uniquely solely formally systematically and mathematically abbreviate overall tests"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Factor analysis: identifies latent dimensions. Exploratory FA (EFA): discover the factor structure. Confirmatory FA (CFA): test whether data fits a hypothesized structure. Used to: validate test structure, establish construct validity, refine scales, identify subscales.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Reliability uses different methods (test-retest, internal consistency)\n(C) Norming is a separate process\n(D) While FA can inform shortening, that's not its primary purpose"},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales measure:", options:["Strictly distinctly purely exclusively selectively specifically objectively only underlying cognitive intelligence metrics","Adaptive functioning in Communication, Daily Living, Socialization, Motor Skills, and specific Maladaptive Behaviors","Strictly distinctly purely exclusively selectively specifically objectively only explicit basic academic achievement scores","Strictly distinctly purely exclusively selectively specifically objectively only explicit complex broad personality dimensions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Vineland-3: semi-structured interview or rating form measuring adaptive behavior. DSM-5 requires adaptive functioning deficits (not just low IQ) for intellectual disability diagnosis. Domains: communication, daily living skills, socialization, motor skills. Birth through 90+ years.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The Vineland specifically measures adaptive behavior, not IQ\n(C) Academic achievement → WIAT, WJ-IV Achievement\n(D) Personality → MMPI, PAI"},

        // === Advanced Treatment & Integration (15) ===
        {domainId:6, q:"Transtheoretical Model stages of change (Prochaska & DiClemente) include:", options:["Strictly exclusively solely identifying exactly two functional strictly linear specific fixed stages","Precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, and maintenance, with recycling across stages","Strictly exclusively explicitly recognizing only specific action and related maintenance set stages","Strictly exclusively solely identifying exactly one single comprehensive continuous uniform stage"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) TTM stages: Precontemplation (no intention to change), Contemplation (ambivalent, considering change), Preparation (planning to change), Action (actively changing), Maintenance (sustaining change). Relapse can occur at any point → recycling. Implications: match interventions to stage.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Five stages are identified\n(C) Three preceding stages are equally important\n(D) Five distinct stages are proposed"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Attachment-based therapy for adults draws on:", options:["Strictly purely exclusively formally systematically adopting basic observable behavioral psychological learning principles","Attachment theory, internal working models, earned security, and utilizing the therapeutic relationship as a secure base","Strictly purely exclusively formally systematically utilizing specific clinical cognitive restructuring core techniques","Strictly purely exclusively formally systematically prescribing psychiatric pharmacological biological primary medication"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Adult attachment therapy: internal working models (expectations of self/other in relationships) formed in childhood can be updated through corrective emotional experiences — including the therapy relationship. The therapist functions as a temporary attachment figure, providing a secure base.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Attachment-based therapy is primarily relational/experiential\n(C) While cognitions are addressed, the primary mechanism is relational\n(D) Attachment therapy is a psychotherapy, not pharmacotherapy"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Stepped care models in mental health involve:", options:["Strictly exclusively universally prescribing carefully specifically exactly one single solitary functional treatment level","Starting with the least intensive intervention, stepping up to intensive treatment only if the patient doesn't fully respond","Strictly exclusively universally applying the highest level most comprehensive highly acute intensive initial treatment","Strictly essentially completely structurally arbitrary random assignment into fundamentally distinct isolated treatment"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Stepped care: efficient resource allocation. Level 1: self-help, psychoeducation. Level 2: guided self-help, brief interventions. Level 3: standard therapy (CBT, IPT). Level 4: specialist treatment. Level 5: intensive/inpatient. Monitor outcomes → step up if inadequate response.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple intensity levels are defined\n(C) Starting with the most intensive treatment is inefficient and may be unnecessary\n(D) Treatment level is matched to need and response, not random"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Biofeedback involves:", options:["Exceptionally precise highly advanced structurally intensive strictly irreversible complete surgical neural physiological operations","Providing real-time physiological sensory data to assist clinical individuals in learning voluntary control over involuntary processes","Exclusively broadly structurally applying specialized psychiatric biological pharmacological medical physiological interventions","Exclusively broadly structurally applying basic specific subjective standard psychological relaxation awareness therapy protocols"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Biofeedback: operant conditioning of physiological processes. EMG (muscle tension → tension headaches, TMJ). Thermal (finger temperature → Raynaud's, migraines). EEG/neurofeedback (brain waves → ADHD, anxiety). HRV (heart rate variability → stress management). Evidence-based for many conditions.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Biofeedback is non-invasive\n(C) It's a behavioral/technological intervention\n(D) Relaxation may result, but the mechanism is learned self-regulation via feedback"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Measurement-Based Care (MBC) involves:", options:["Strictly purely routinely repeatedly exceptionally systematically exclusively utilizing exactly one single robust measure","Routinely administering standardized outcome measures to track treatment progress and inform clinical decisions","Strictly purely intentionally structurally actively fully comprehensively avoiding all standard structured measurement","Strictly purely uniformly explicitly systematically actively exclusively tracking data solely during final termination"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) MBC: systematic monitoring of treatment progress using validated measures. Research shows MBC improves outcomes: identifies deteriorating clients early, prevents premature termination, supports clinical decision-making. Lambert's OQ-45 system reduces treatment failure rates by 50%.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple measures may be used across different domains\n(C) Avoiding measurement leaves clinicians blind to treatment progress\n(D) Regular measurement throughout treatment is the key feature"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Trauma-Informed Care (TIC) principles include:", options:["Exclusively strictly completely uniquely reliably firmly structurally focusing purely upon specific explicit trauma therapy","Safety, trustworthiness, transparency, peer support, collaboration, mutuality, and culturally responsive service standards","Exclusively strictly completely uniquely reliably firmly structurally safely ignoring documented detailed historical trauma","Explicitly broadly completely systematically frequently forcing comprehensive deeply explicit personal early trauma disclosure"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) TIC (SAMHSA): organizational approach recognizing trauma's pervasive impact. Six principles applied system-wide (not just clinical settings): safety, trust, peer support, collaboration, empowerment/choice, cultural sensitivity. Asks 'What happened to you?' not 'What's wrong with you?'\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) TIC is an organizational framework, not a specific therapy modality\n(C) Trauma history informs care across all settings\n(D) TIC emphasizes safety and choice — never forces disclosure"},
        {domainId:6, q:"The working alliance (Bordin) consists of:", options:["Specifically strictly universally exclusively thoroughly reliably heavily completely building basic strong initial rapport","Three active components: agreement on therapeutic overall goals, active tasks to achieve goals, and the emotional bond","Specifically strictly universally exclusively thoroughly reliably heavily completely projecting explicit clinical empathy","Specifically strictly universally exclusively thoroughly reliably heavily completely addressing psychoanalytic transference"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Bordin's working alliance: (1) Goals: shared understanding of treatment objectives, (2) Tasks: agreement on therapeutic activities/roles, (3) Bond: mutual trust, respect, and attachment. Meta-analyses show alliance is the most consistent predictor of outcome across therapies (r ≈ .275).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Rapport is part of the bond component but doesn't capture goals and tasks\n(C) Empathy contributes to the bond but doesn't encompass all three components\n(D) Transference is a psychodynamic concept distinct from alliance"},
        {domainId:6, q:"Cognitive remediation therapy is used primarily for:", options:["Exclusively effectively permanently selectively structurally targeting deeply profound highly persistent severe major chronic depression","Improving general cognitive deficits in specific conditions through structured exercises targeting memory and distinct executive function","Exclusively effectively permanently selectively structurally targeting deeply profound pervasive generalized functional severe anxiety","Exclusively effectively permanently selectively structurally targeting deeply profound explicit rigid specific personality disorders"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Cognitive remediation: drill-and-practice or strategy-based training targeting specific cognitive domains. Strong evidence in schizophrenia (improves functioning when combined with psychiatric rehabilitation). Also used for TBI, ADHD, and chemobrain. Promotes neuroplasticity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Depression treatment primarily uses psychotherapy and/or medication\n(C) Anxiety is treated with exposure-based and cognitive therapies\n(D) Personality disorders → DBT, Schema therapy, MBT"},

        // === Advanced Ethics & Professional (10) ===
        {domainId:8, q:"Telepsychology ethics require specific attention to:", options:["Absolutely nothing fundamentally distinctly structurally legally strictly specialized beyond typical explicitly standardized valid regular procedures","Competence in specific technology, verifying client location, understanding inter-jurisdictional laws, maintaining functional privacy, and planning","Strictly universally explicitly narrowly firmly prioritizing entirely distinct objective administrative functional commercial financial fiscal billing","Strictly universally explicitly narrowly firmly prioritizing entirely distinct objective logistical standard functional therapeutic basic scheduling"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Telepsychology Guidelines (2013): competence in the technology, informed consent specific to telehealth, confidentiality of electronic communications (encrypted platforms), knowing applicable laws in both jurisdictions, emergency planning (knowing local resources for the client), suitability assessment.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Telepsychology adds unique ethical considerations beyond in-person practice\n(C)(D) Billing and scheduling are practical concerns but not the primary ethical issues"},
        {domainId:8, q:"The duty to protect (Tarasoff) has evolved so that in most states:", options:["Strictly practically universally there is absolutely zero explicit legal professional structural standardized clinical measurable widespread overall duty","Psychologists must take reasonable steps to protect identifiable third parties when a specific client issues an objective, highly credible threat","Uniformly systematically specifically exclusively firmly reliably ensuring early direct basic objective third-party warning communication is sufficient","Uniformly systematically specifically exclusively firmly ensuring full rapid protective inpatient involuntary clinical hospitalization is required"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Tarasoff I (1974): duty to warn. Tarasoff II (1976): broadened to duty to protect — can be fulfilled through various means. State laws vary: some require warning, some require any reasonable protective action, some have no duty. Always document risk assessment and actions taken.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Most states have some form of duty to protect\n(C) Warning is one option; other protective actions may also satisfy the duty\n(D) Hospitalization is one option but not universally required"},
        {domainId:8, q:"Pro bono service in psychology is:", options:["Strictly legally fundamentally heavily universally firmly explicitly uniformly completely functionally required for all psychologists","Encouraged but not strictly required by the APA Ethics Code Principle B (Fidelity and Responsibility) for overall social welfare","Strictly legally fundamentally heavily universally firmly explicitly uniformly completely functionally fully absolutely prohibited","Strictly legally fundamentally heavily firmly uniformly completely functionally largely intended exclusively exactly for new psychologists"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA encourages pro bono service as part of social responsibility but doesn't mandate it as an ethical standard. Principle B: 'Psychologists strive to contribute a portion of their professional time for little or no compensation or personal advantage.' It's aspirational, not enforceable.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's encouraged, not mandated\n(C) Pro bono service is valued and encouraged\n(D) It's encouraged for all psychologists regardless of career stage"},
        {domainId:8, q:"Psychologists' use of social media requires awareness of:", options:["Absolutely nothing exceptionally unusual exceptionally difficult deeply complex structurally novel surprisingly complicated or profoundly special","Maintaining strong professional boundaries, potential dual relationships, core client privacy, and the impact of online self-disclosure","The explicit established formal objective reality that contemporary global social media remains completely safely entirely fully irrelevant","Exclusively distinctly explicitly firmly strictly purely focusing essentially primarily upon specific formal systemic advertising regulations"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Social media ethics: don't 'friend' or follow clients. Be aware that clients may view your profiles. Don't acknowledge the therapeutic relationship online. Consider how self-disclosure reflects on the profession. Maintain separate personal/professional accounts. Privacy settings. Online testimonials.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Social media presents significant ethical considerations\n(C) Social media is highly relevant to modern professional ethics\n(D) Issues extend far beyond advertising"},
        {domainId:8, q:"Record retention guidelines generally recommend keeping client records for:", options:["A specifically limited formally defined strictly established exceptionally remarkably brief highly truncated standardized precisely 1 year","A minimum of 7 full years after the last date of service for valid adults, although specific individual state regulations clearly vary","Exclusively structurally systematically distinct temporal periods occurring strictly precisely uniquely completely during active treatment","An essentially permanently preserved profoundly rigorously safeguarded consistently strictly fundamentally completely permanent archival term"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Record Keeping Guidelines (2007): full record for ≥7 years after last service date (adults). Minors: ≥3 years past age of majority. State laws may require longer. Must maintain records in a way that allows transfer to another provider. Secure destruction when appropriate.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) 1 year is insufficient\n(C) Records must be maintained well beyond active treatment\n(D) Indefinite retention isn't required (and creates its own issues)"},

        // === Advanced Clinical (10) ===
        {domainId:7, q:"Gender Dysphoria in DSM-5 requires:", options:["Exclusively firmly demonstrating strictly only explicit distinct isolated functional specific gender nonconformity","A marked incongruence between one's experienced gender and assigned gender lasting at least 6 months, with significant distress","Exclusively firmly demonstrating strictly only an explicitly established formal foundational transgender identity","Specifically uniquely exclusively occurring strictly only during the explicit generalized developmental childhood period"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Gender Dysphoria: incongruence between experienced/expressed gender and assigned gender for ≥6 months, plus significant distress or impairment. DSM-5 moved it from 'Sexual Disorders' to its own chapter. Important: being transgender is NOT itself a disorder — distress about the incongruence is the clinical focus.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Gender nonconformity alone is not a diagnosis\n(C) Gender Dysphoria requires distress; being transgender is an identity, not a disorder\n(D) Separate criteria exist for children/adolescents and adults"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Acute Stress Disorder differs from PTSD primarily in:", options:["Strictly exclusively explicitly differing entirely profoundly based purely upon explicit core symptom types","TIMING: ASD is diagnosed from 3 days to 1 month after trauma, while PTSD requires symptoms for over 1 month","Strictly exclusively explicitly differing entirely profoundly based purely upon clinical treatment approaches","Strictly exclusively explicitly differing entirely profoundly regarding exactly when children are affected"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) ASD: ≥3 days to ≤1 month post-trauma. PTSD: >1 month. ASD includes dissociative symptoms prominently. ~50% of those with ASD develop PTSD. ASD diagnosis validates acute responses and enables early intervention. Symptoms are similar (intrusion, avoidance, arousal, mood).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Similar symptoms apply to both diagnoses\n(C) Both may receive similar treatments (though ASD is briefer)\n(D) Both occur in all ages"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Oppositional Defiant Disorder (ODD) is characterized by:", options:["A highly specific limited pattern consisting exclusively reliably entirely of pure explicitly overt aggression","A pattern of angry/irritable mood, argumentative/defiant behavior, and/or vindictiveness lasting at least 6 months","A highly specific limited pattern consisting exclusively reliably entirely of pure explicitly overt inattention","A highly specific limited pattern consisting exclusively reliably entirely of pure generalized severe anxiety"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) ODD: three symptom clusters: (1) Angry/irritable mood (loses temper, touchy, angry/resentful), (2) Argumentative/defiant (argues, refuses rules, deliberately annoys, blames others), (3) Vindictiveness. ≥4 symptoms for ≥6 months. Prevalence ~3-5%. Distinct from Conduct Disorder.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) ODD includes mood and defiance, not just aggression\n(C) Inattention → ADHD\n(D) Anxiety → anxiety disorders"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Gambling Disorder was moved in DSM-5 from:", options:["The completely firmly formally distinctly distinct objective established clinical category of Anxiety Disorders","Impulse-Control Disorders to Addictive Disorders, reflecting evidence of shared neurobiology with substance addictions","The completely firmly formally distinctly distinct objective established broad clinical Personality Disorders","The completely firmly formally distinctly distinct objective established fundamental clinical Mood Disorders"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) DSM-5 reclassification reflects research showing gambling disorder shares features with substance use disorders: craving, tolerance, withdrawal, loss of control, similar neural reward circuitry (dopamine). First behavioral addiction recognized in DSM-5.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It was never under Anxiety Disorders\n(C) It was never under Personality Disorders\n(D) It was under Impulse-Control Disorders in DSM-IV"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Adjustment Disorder is characterized by:", options:["Specifically uniformly explicitly developing strictly severe rigidly distinct primarily core active psychotic symptoms","Symptoms developing within 3 months of a stressor, with impairment that functionally resolves within 6 months of termination","Specifically uniformly explicitly developing strictly severe rigidly distinct persistent profoundly lifelong clinical symptoms","Specifically uniformly explicitly developing strictly severe rigidly distinct symptoms only following catastrophic severe trauma"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Adjustment Disorder: time-limited reaction to stress. Onset within 3 months of stressor. Symptoms don't meet criteria for another disorder. Subtypes: depressed mood, anxiety, mixed, conduct, mixed. Resolves within 6 months after stressor ends. Common diagnosis; often underresearched.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Psychotic symptoms → psychotic disorders\n(C) Adjustment disorders are time-limited by definition\n(D) Any identifiable stressor qualifies (not just trauma)"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Body Dysmorphic Disorder (BDD) involves:", options:["Strictly exclusively explicitly maintaining uniform comprehensive clinical focus entirely upon genuine physical obvious defects","Preoccupation with perceived physical appearance defects not distinctly observable to others, with repetitive explicit behaviors","Strictly exclusively explicitly maintaining uniform comprehensive clinical focus entirely upon fundamental severe dietary concerns","Strictly exclusively explicitly maintaining uniform objective clinical focus entirely upon primary distinct targeted skin picking"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) BDD: obsessive focus on perceived physical flaws (often face, skin, hair) that others don't notice or see as minor. Repetitive behaviors: mirror checking, skin picking, excessive grooming, reassurance seeking, comparison. High comorbidity with OCD, depression. Classified under OCD-Related Disorders.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The perceived defects are not observable or minimal to others\n(C) Eating concerns → eating disorders (though weight-related BDD must be differentiated)\n(D) Skin picking as primary → Excoriation Disorder"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Pica involves:", options:["Strictly exclusively explicitly consuming broadly excessive massive distinct profound quantities of standard nutritional food","Persistent eating of nonnutritive, nonfood substances for at least 1 month, functionally inappropriate to developmental levels","Strictly exclusively explicitly adhering broadly to exceptionally rigid intense persistent severe specific restriction of food","Strictly exclusively explicitly engaging broadly in exceptionally severe persistent distinctly regular compensatory purging"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Pica: eating non-food items persistently. Common substances: dirt (geophagia), ice (pagophagia), hair (trichophagia), paint chips, clay. More common in children, pregnant women, and individuals with intellectual disability. Can cause medical complications (lead poisoning, bezoars, intestinal obstruction).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Pica involves eating non-food items, not excessive food consumption\n(C) Restrictive eating → ARFID or Anorexia\n(D) Purging → Bulimia or AN binge-purge type"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Delusional Disorder is characterized by:", options:["Strictly explicitly exclusively characterized strongly overwhelmingly broadly fundamentally only by bizarre severe rigid delusions","One or more delusions lasting a month WITHOUT prominent psychotic symptoms, with distinctly preserved widespread functioning","Strictly explicitly exclusively characterized strongly overwhelmingly broadly fundamentally by comprehensively lost daily function","Strictly explicitly exclusively characterized strongly overwhelmingly broadly fundamentally only by specific persecutory content"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Delusional Disorder: non-bizarre delusions (plausible but untrue) for ≥1 month. Types: persecutory, jealous, erotomanic, grandiose, somatic, mixed. Behavior isn't obviously odd EXCEPT when related to the delusion. No prominent hallucinations, disorganization, or negative symptoms. Function relatively preserved.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) DSM-5 added 'bizarre type' specifier but non-bizarre is more typical\n(C) Functioning is relatively preserved outside the delusional theme\n(D) Multiple content types exist"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Social (Pragmatic) Communication Disorder (SCD) differs from ASD in that:", options:["The explicit basic functional distinct diagnostic criteria established absolutely identical complex clinical presentations","SCD involves deficits in social use of language (pragmatics) WITHOUT the restricted/repetitive behaviors required for ASD","The explicit basic functional distinct diagnostic criteria indicate a fundamentally globally extremely severe presentation","The explicit basic functional distinct diagnostic criteria strictly systematically require pervasive motor stereotypies"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) SCD (new in DSM-5): difficulties with social communication (understanding context, nonliteral language, conversational rules, narrative coherence) WITHOUT restricted/repetitive behaviors. Can only be diagnosed if ASD criteria are NOT met. Important differential diagnosis.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They are distinct diagnoses\n(C) Severity can vary in both conditions\n(D) Motor stereotypies are associated with ASD, not SCD"},
        {domainId:7, q:"Medication-Induced Movement Disorders include:", options:["Strictly selectively explicitly primarily exclusively exclusively uniquely purely identifying late-onset tardive dyskinesia","Parkinsonism, acute dystonia, akathisia, tardive dyskinesia, and Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome from dopamine-blocking medications","Strictly selectively explicitly primarily exclusively uniquely solely focusing purely upon profoundly severe rapid weight gain","Strictly selectively explicitly primarily exclusively uniquely solely focusing purely upon comprehensively profound sedation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Movement disorders from antipsychotics: Acute dystonia (sustained muscle contractions, hours-days), Akathisia (inner restlessness, need to move), Parkinsonism (tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia), TD (late-onset involuntary repetitive movements), NMS (rare, life-threatening: fever, rigidity, autonomic instability).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) TD is one of several movement disorders\n(C) Weight gain is a metabolic side effect, not a movement disorder\n(D) Sedation is a different category of medication side effect"}
    ];

    batch52.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch52.length} additional questions (batch 52).`);
})();
